snippet.textDisplay:
Joe Rogan is 100 percent correct in that martial arts is different than the other sports. In football, baseball, basketball, etc the personalities are much different, the locker room is different, training is different. You can be a dick in these sports. In martial arts, you can't be a dick(unless it's for show to get money). Some of the nicest people in the world are fighters. I trained at a couple different places and almost everyone is just overly nice. Martial arts has a lot to do with respect and kindness. Conor/Colby talk a lot of shit and make fun because it's what brings in money. But in person, they're just as nice as the rest of us.


It's a very violent sport, to say a team sucked because they couldn't throw a ball into a hoop enough times is much different than saying someone sucks who just got in there, got broken bones, getting punched, etc.

snippet.textDisplay:
Generally, I agree with what you're saying. I'm a long time fan, I study material arts almost my whole life. Generally, I felt Cerrone was being fed to the wolves. That was his role in the fight. He's a great man and a great fighter but he's a little past his prime, a little broken down and really has lost his desire to fight, in my opinion.
Just like when they fed him to Gaeghje. They're using his status to boost up other fighters now. Or that's how it appears. They are pretty certain he will lose and it'll bringe more popularity and credibility to any fighter who dominates him.
The only reason I can slightly agree with Stephen is because once Cerrone fell back agaisnt the cage towards the end of the fight, Connor wasn't even hitting him at that moment, but he just fell over and layed down and gave up. He didn't want anymore. It appeared that he knew his role was to take an ass beating from Connor to make Connor appear dominat again and he accepted that and fell over and gave up. Most of the time when someone wants to fight, it's in those moments, when there's a pause that they stand up and fight back. Unfortunately, Cerrone didn't appear to want to fight.
